{
  "id": "math155-lawcos2-001",
  "cid": "MATH 155",
  "topic": "Analytic Trigonometry",
  "subtopic": "Law of Cosines \u2014 find missing angle",
  "difficulty": 3,
  "license": "CC BY-NC-SA (Numberbender original)",
  "instruction": "In triangle ABC, a = {side_a}, b = {side_b}, c = {side_c}. Use the Law of Cosines to find angle C in degrees (round to 1 decimal place).",
  "params": {
    "side_a": {
      "type": "int",
      "min": 4,
      "max": 9
    },
    "side_b": {
      "type": "int",
      "min": 4,
      "max": 9
    },
    "side_c": {
      "type": "int",
      "min": 4,
      "max": 9
    }
  },
  "answer_expr": "lawcos2",
  "steps": [
    "Rearrange the Law of Cosines for angle C:",
    "cos(C) = (a^2 + b^2 - c^2) / (2ab) = ({side_a}^2 + {side_b}^2 - {side_c}^2) / (2*{side_a}*{side_b}).",
    "cos(C) = ({a2} + {b2} - {c2}) / {two_ab} = {cos_C_val}.",
    "C = arccos({cos_C_val}) = {answer_lawcos2}\u00b0."
  ],
  "tags": [
    "law-of-cosines",
